Q1. read.csv (base R) vs read_csv (tidyverse) vs fread (data.table)

There are quite a few utilities in R for reading plain text data files. Let us test the speed of reading a moderate sized compressed csv file, admissions.csv.gz, by three programs: read.csv in base R, read_csv in tidyverse, and fread in the popular data.table package.

system.time(read.csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/core/admissions.csv.gz"))
system.time(read_csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/core/admissions.csv.gz"))
system.time(fread("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/core/admissions.csv.gz"))

Which function is fastest? Is there difference in the (default) parsed data types? (Hint: R function system.time measures run times.)

Solution: The fread function is fastest, followed clsoely by read_csv. read.csv was the slowest by more than a factor of ten. read_csv classifies the time variables as date time data types whereas read.csv classifies these by default as numeric.

For later questions, we stick to the tidyverse.

  1. Summarize the following variables by graphics.
  • admission year
admissions_tble$admit_year <- year(admissions_tble$admittime)
ggplot(data = admissions_tble) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(admit_year))

  • admission month
admissions_tble$admit_month <- month(admissions_tble$admittime, label = TRUE)
ggplot(data = admissions_tble) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(admit_month))

  • admission month day
admissions_tble$admit_mday <- mday(admissions_tble$admittime)
ggplot(data = admissions_tble) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(admit_mday))

  • admission week day
admissions_tble$admit_wday <- wday(admissions_tble$admittime, label = TRUE)
ggplot(data = admissions_tble) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(admit_wday))

  • admission hour (anything unusual?)
admissions_tble$admit_hour <- hour(admissions_tble$admittime)
ggplot(data = admissions_tble) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(admit_hour))

Solution: There is a large spike in admissions at 7am compared to the hours preceding and following it. This could be when most people wake up and decide they need to go to the hospital, when there is a staffing increase at the hospital for the beginning of the work day, or another unknown factor.

  1. We are interested in the lab measurements of creatinine (50912), potassium (50971), sodium (50983), chloride (50902), bicarbonate (50882), hematocrit (51221), white blood cell count (51301), glucose (50931), magnesium (50960), and calcium (50893). Retrieve a subset of labevents.csv.gz only containing these items for the patients in icustays_tble as a tibble labevents_tble.

    Hint: labevents.csv.gz is a data file too big to be read in by the read_csv function in its default setting. Utilize the col_select and lazy options in the read_csv function to reduce the memory burden.

labevents_tble <- read_csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/hosp/labevents_filtered_itemid.csv.gz")

  1. Further restrict labevents_tble to the first lab measurement during the ICU stay.
labevents_tble <- labevents_tble %>% 
                     group_by(subject_id) %>% 
                     arrange(charttime) %>% 
                     distinct(subject_id, .keep_all = TRUE)
labevents_tble <- labevents_tble %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = itemid, 
              values_from = valuenum)
  1. Summarize the lab measurements by appropriate numerics and graphics.
names(labevents_tble) <- c('subject_id', 'charttime', 'bicarbonate',

lab_means <- labevents_tble %>%

lab_medians <- labevents_tble %>%

                 median, na.rm = TRUE)

lab_sd <- labevents_tble %>%
  summarise_at(c("bicarbonate", "chloride", "creatinine", "glucose", 
                 "potassium", "sodium", "hematocrit", "white_blood_cell_count",
                 "calcium", "magnesium"), 
                 sd, na.rm = TRUE)

lab_min <- labevents_tble %>%
  summarise_at(c("bicarbonate", "chloride", "creatinine", "glucose",

Q7. Putting things together

Let us create a tibble mimic_icu_cohort for all ICU stays, where rows are

  • first ICU stay of each unique adult (age at admission > 18)

and columns contain at least following variables

  • all variables in icustays.csv.gz
  • all variables in admission.csv.gz
  • all variables in patients.csv.gz
  • first lab measurements during ICU stay
  • first vital measurements during ICU stay
  • an indicator variable thirty_day_mort whether the patient died within 30 days of hospital admission (30 day mortality)

  • thirty_day_mort vs first vital measurements
